window.BASKET_DATA = {"groups":[{"code":"MSN","name":"Mission Analysis & Flight Dynamics","blurb":"Trajectory, recovery, balloon sizing and launch operations."},{"code":"AVI","name":"Avionics, OBC & Electrical Power","blurb":"Flight computer, power system and radio link hardware."},{"code":"STR","name":"Structure & Thermal Control","blurb":"Enclosures, thermal design and environmental test rigs."},{"code":"MEC","name":"Mechanisms & Actuation","blurb":"Cut-down, gimbals, antenna rotators and sampling hardware."},{"code":"DHA","name":"Data Handling & Analytics","blurb":"Telemetry pipelines, dashboards and post-flight analysis."},{"code":"PLD","name":"Science Payload \u2014 Atmospheric Physics","blurb":"Pressure, temperature, radiation and cosmic-ray sensing."},{"code":"PLC","name":"Science Payload \u2014 Chemistry & Materials","blurb":"Air sampling, materials exposure and chemical analysis."},{"code":"SWS","name":"Flight & Ground Software","blurb":"Onboard flight software and ground control software stack."},{"code":"AIM","name":"AI / ML & Onboard Intelligence","blurb":"Onboard inference, computer vision and predictive models."},{"code":"GND","name":"Ground Station & Communication","blurb":"Antennas, receivers, link budget and station networking."}],"projects":[{"code":"BSAT-MSN-2026-001","prefix":"MSN","subsystem":"MISSION ANALYSIS & FLIGHT DYNAMICS","title":"Flight Trajectory Prediction & Simulation","skills":"MATLAB/Python, atmosphere models (ISA), CUSF/habhub-style predictors, GFS wind data","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"A latex weather balloon does not fly a straight line \u2014 it drifts with the wind at every layer of the atmosphere, climbing at roughly 5 m/s until it expands from ~2 m to ~10 m diameter and bursts near 30 km. Predicting this path is a classic aerospace problem combining buoyancy, drag, the standard atmosphere and real forecast wind fields (GFS). Your prediction decides the launch site, the recovery plan and whether the mission is even legal to fly that day (it must not drift into airports or restricted zones). The core challenge is that ascent rate and burst altitude are uncertain, so a single predicted path is never enough \u2014 you must understand how errors grow. Start by studying the physics used by the open-source CUSF flight predictor, then build your own simplified model and compare.","scope":"Model the complete flight: ascent rate vs free lift, burst altitude prediction, and descent under parachute. Use GFS wind data to predict the flight path and landing zone. Validate the model against the actual flight and publish prediction-vs-actual error analysis.","deliverables":["Trajectory simulation tool","Pre-launch prediction report","Post-flight validation report"],"linkages":["BSAT-DHA-2026-003, Mission Ops"]},{"code":"BSAT-MSN-2026-002","prefix":"MSN","subsystem":"MISSION ANALYSIS & FLIGHT DYNAMICS","title":"Parachute & Recovery System Design","skills":"Aerodynamics, drag estimation, sewing/fabrication, drop-test experimentation","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"After burst, the payload free-falls in air so thin (1% of sea-level density at 30 km) that the parachute barely works at first \u2014 descent starts at 50+ m/s and slows as the air thickens. Your parachute must deliver a safe 4\u20136 m/s at ground level: too fast destroys the payload, too slow drifts it tens of kilometres further, often into unreachable terrain. This is real aerospace decelerator design: canopy shape selection (hemispherical, cross, toroidal), drag coefficient estimation, and the awkward fact that the parachute must also not tangle with the burst balloon remains above it. The engineering happens in testing \u2014 drop tests are your wind tunnel. Start with the drag equation, size a canopy for your payload mass, and design a test campaign that measures real descent rates.","scope":"Design, size and fabricate the parachute for a 4\u20136 m/s landing descent rate. Analyze drag coefficients, perform drop tests from a building/drone, and design the rigging between balloon, parachute and payload train.","deliverables":["Flight-ready parachute + rigging","Drop test report","Descent rate analysis"],"linkages":["BSAT-STR-2026-003, BSAT-MSN-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-MSN-2026-003","prefix":"MSN","subsystem":"MISSION ANALYSIS & FLIGHT DYNAMICS","title":"Balloon Sizing, Lift Gas & Burst Analysis","skills":"Buoyancy physics, gas laws, safety procedures, trade studies","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Everything about the flight is set at the moment of inflation: how much gas you put in the balloon determines ascent rate, burst altitude and flight duration. Too little lift and the balloon may float for hours and land in another state; too much and it bursts low, wasting the mission. The physics is Archimedes' principle applied to a stretching rubber envelope \u2014 free lift, neck lift, gas density (helium vs hydrogen trade-offs including safety), and the manufacturer's burst diameter data. On launch day, your team is the one holding the balloon, so the deliverable is as much procedure as physics: a repeatable way to measure neck lift in the field with wind blowing. Start with the balloon performance calculators used by the HAB community and re-derive their math yourself.","scope":"Select balloon size (e.g. 800\u20131500 g latex), compute required neck lift and gas volume (helium/hydrogen trade study), predict burst altitude, and write the complete launch-day inflation procedure with a lift measurement rig.","deliverables":["Balloon selection report","Inflation & neck-lift procedure","Launch-day checklist","Burst altitude prediction"],"linkages":["BSAT-MSN-2026-001, Launch Ops"]},{"code":"BSAT-MSN-2026-004","prefix":"MSN","subsystem":"MISSION ANALYSIS & FLIGHT DYNAMICS","title":"Payload Train Dynamics & Stability","skills":"Rigid body dynamics, IMU data analysis, mechanical design","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"Video from most amateur balloon flights is dizzying \u2014 the payload spins and swings like a pendulum under a 30\u201390 m line to the balloon. Understanding why is a genuine dynamics problem: the payload train is a multi-body pendulum excited by wind shear and vortex shedding from the balloon. Reducing the motion matters for camera footage, for the stabilized gimbal team (BSAT-MEC-2026-002), and for scientific sensors that assume a known orientation. Countermeasures include swivels, fins, longer/shorter lines, and mass distribution changes \u2014 but you must model and measure before you fix. The IMU flying on the payload gives you real rotation-rate data to validate against. Start by modeling the train as a double pendulum and identifying its natural frequencies.","scope":"Study and reduce spin/pendulum motion of the payload during ascent so cameras stay stable. Design the payload train layout (balloon\u2013parachute\u2013radar reflector\u2013payload spacing), swivels and anti-rotation measures. Validate with IMU data from the flight.","deliverables":["Payload train design document","Anti-spin hardware","Post-flight imu stability analysis"],"linkages":["BSAT-MEC-2026-002, BSAT-AVI-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-MSN-2026-005","prefix":"MSN","subsystem":"MISSION ANALYSIS & FLIGHT DYNAMICS","title":"Mission Design, Regulations & Launch Operations","skills":"Systems engineering, regulatory research, project management, risk analysis","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Someone must own the mission as a whole \u2014 this is the systems engineering role that turns all the subsystem teams' projects into one flight. A high-altitude balloon shares airspace with aircraft, so this project owns the legal side: aviation authority notification (NOTAM), payload mass and line-strength rules, and no-fly-zone analysis. It also owns the master budgets (mass, power, radio bandwidth) that every other team must fit inside, the risk register, and the minute-by-minute launch day plan. It is the least 'build' and most 'engineer' project in the basket, and the best preparation for how real space missions are actually run. Start by reading your country's uncrewed free balloon regulations and writing the top-level mission requirements document.","scope":"Own the overall mission: requirements document, mass/power/link budgets roll-up, aviation authority permissions (NOTAM), launch site selection, go/no-go weather criteria, launch-day operations plan and recovery/chase plan.","deliverables":["Mission requirements document","Regulatory approvals file","Launch & recovery operations manual","Risk register"],"linkages":["All teams"]},{"code":"BSAT-AVI-2026-001","prefix":"AVI","subsystem":"AVIONICS, OBC & ELECTRICAL POWER SYSTEM","title":"Flight Computer Design & PCB Development","skills":"KiCad/Altium, embedded C, PCB assembly & debugging, schematic design","difficulty":"Advanced  |  4 students","summary":"The flight computer is the heart of the BalloonSat: it reads every sensor, logs the data, feeds the radio and must not crash once during a 3-hour mission where nobody can press reset. At 30 km it faces conditions no classroom project sees: \u221260 \u00b0C ambient, condensation during descent through clouds, battery voltage sagging in the cold, and increased radiation. Designing it means choosing a microcontroller, drawing schematics, laying out a PCB with proper power and connector design, and proving robustness with watchdogs and brown-out handling. The discipline is what matters: version-controlled hardware, bring-up checklists, and a spare unit identical to the flight unit. Start by listing every subsystem that needs power, pins or data \u2014 the flight computer is defined by its interfaces.","scope":"Design the main flight computer: microcontroller selection (e.g. STM32/ATmega/RP2040), custom PCB with sensor headers, SD logging, watchdog and brown-out protection. Take it from schematic to assembled, environment-tested board.","deliverables":["Assembled flight computer PCB (2 units: flight + spare)","Schematics","Test report"],"linkages":["BSAT-SWS-2026-001, BSAT-AVI-2026-002, BSAT-AVI-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-AVI-2026-002","prefix":"AVI","subsystem":"AVIONICS, OBC & ELECTRICAL POWER SYSTEM","title":"Power System for Extreme Cold","skills":"Power electronics, battery characterization, DC-DC converters, thermal testing","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Batteries are chemical devices, and chemistry nearly stops at stratospheric temperatures \u2014 a battery that delivers full capacity on the bench can die in minutes at \u221240 \u00b0C. This project owns the mission's energy: choosing a chemistry that works cold (lithium primary cells like Li-FeS\u2082 are the HAB standard), computing the full mission energy budget with margin, designing efficient regulation and distribution, and protecting against shorts in a foam box you cannot open in flight. The proof is experimental: your cold-chamber endurance tests (with the BSAT-PLC-2026-004 cold-test data) decide the flight battery. A power failure kills every other team's project simultaneously, so redundancy thinking is essential. Start by measuring the real current draw of each subsystem prototype, not the datasheet numbers.","scope":"Design the power subsystem: energy budget for 3+ hour mission, battery chemistry trade study (Li-primary vs Li-ion at \u221240 \u00b0C), regulators, power distribution, current monitoring, and cold-chamber (dry ice) endurance testing.","deliverables":["Power distribution board","Battery cold-test report","Mission power budget spreadsheet"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-001, BSAT-STR-2026-002, All payloads"]},{"code":"BSAT-AVI-2026-003","prefix":"AVI","subsystem":"AVIONICS, OBC & ELECTRICAL POWER SYSTEM","title":"Telemetry Radio Link (LoRa / APRS)","skills":"RF basics, LoRa/packet radio, antenna fundamentals, link budget math","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"The radio link is the mission's lifeline \u2014 30+ km of slant range on milliwatts of power, from a transmitter dangling under a balloon to your ground station. LoRa modulation makes this possible for students: its spread-spectrum design decodes signals below the noise floor, so a 25 mW 433 MHz transmitter can reach hundreds of kilometres line-of-sight. Your challenges are the airborne antenna (a quarter-wave wire must be tuned and polarized correctly while swinging), the link budget, and regulatory limits on power and duty cycle. Ground range testing is deceptive \u2014 a few km on the ground with obstacles roughly equals hundreds airborne with clear line-of-sight, and you must quantify that. Start with the Friis transmission equation and a pair of LoRa modules on the bench.","scope":"Build the airborne transmitter: LoRa 433 MHz (and/or APRS if amateur licensed) sending GPS + sensor packets. Design the airborne antenna, perform range tests (ground-to-ground several km), and characterize the real link budget.","deliverables":["Flight transmitter module + airborne antenna","Range test report","Packet format spec (with bsat-sws-2026-004)"],"linkages":["BSAT-GND-2026-001, BSAT-GND-2026-003, BSAT-SWS-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-AVI-2026-004","prefix":"AVI","subsystem":"AVIONICS, OBC & ELECTRICAL POWER SYSTEM","title":"Flight Sensor Suite Integration","skills":"Sensor interfacing (I2C/SPI), calibration methods, GPS (airborne dynamic mode), soldering","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"A BalloonSat is a flying instrument cluster, and instruments are only as good as their calibration. This project integrates the core sensor stack: GPS (which must support 'airborne' dynamic mode \u2014 most consumer GPS chips stop reporting above 18 km due to export rules), barometric pressure (which becomes altitude), internal/external temperature, humidity, UV and a 9-axis IMU. Each sensor has quirks: thermistors self-heat, pressure sensors drift with temperature, magnetometers see the payload's own electronics. Your job is characterizing and correcting these effects so the science-payload and data-handling teams get trustworthy numbers. Start by building one clean I2C/SPI bus plan with the flight computer team, then calibrate sensors one at a time against references.","scope":"Select, calibrate and integrate the sensor stack: GPS (high-altitude capable, >18 km), pressure/temperature (internal+external), humidity, UV index, and 9-axis IMU. Deliver calibration curves and an I2C/SPI wiring harness for the flight computer.","deliverables":["Calibrated sensor harness","Calibration report per sensor","Sensor datasheet pack"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-001, BSAT-PLD-2026-002, BSAT-SWS-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-AVI-2026-005","prefix":"AVI","subsystem":"AVIONICS, OBC & ELECTRICAL POWER SYSTEM","title":"Redundant Backup Tracker","skills":"Embedded systems, GSM/SIM modules, low-power design","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Ask any HAB team about their worst moment and it is the silence after the main tracker stops transmitting. Payloads land in trees, ditches and fields where the main antenna is crushed or shadowed \u2014 recovery then depends entirely on an independent backup. This project builds a tracker that shares nothing with the main system: its own battery, its own GPS, and a GSM modem that texts the landing position once it descends into cell coverage (GSM works near the ground, not at altitude \u2014 understanding why is part of the project). Add a buzzer and strobe for the last 50 metres of the search, often in crops taller than you. The engineering theme is independence and low power. Start by testing GSM cold-start behavior after hours without signal.","scope":"Build an independent, self-powered backup tracker so the payload is never lost: separate GPS + GSM (SMS position after landing) and/or a second low-power LoRa beacon, plus audio buzzer and LED strobe for final ground search.","deliverables":["Flight-ready backup tracker (independent battery)","Recovery test report"],"linkages":["Recovery team, BSAT-SWS-2026-005"]},{"code":"BSAT-STR-2026-001","prefix":"STR","subsystem":"STRUCTURE & THERMAL CONTROL","title":"Payload Structure & Enclosure Design","skills":"SolidWorks/Fusion 360, 3D printing, foam fabrication, mass budgeting","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"The payload box must survive \u221260 \u00b0C, a violent burst event, a 5 m/s ground impact \u2014 and weigh almost nothing, because every gram of structure steals a gram from science payloads. The HAB-standard solution is extruded polystyrene foam (light, insulating, crushable on impact) combined with 3D-printed fittings where precision is needed. This project owns the mechanical architecture: internal layout so cameras see out and antennas radiate down, access for last-minute battery swaps on the launch field, and the master mass budget with authority to push back on overweight subsystems. Packaging nine teams' hardware into ~2 kg is a genuine spacecraft-configuration problem. Start by collecting every subsystem's dimensions and building a CAD mock-up before cutting any foam.","scope":"Design the payload box: foam/3D-printed hybrid structure, internal component layout, camera ports, antenna feed-throughs, access hatches. Manage the overall mass budget (\u22642 kg) and produce full CAD of the assembled payload.","deliverables":["Flight enclosure (+1 spare)","Full cad assembly","Mass budget tracking sheet"],"linkages":["All flying subsystems"]},{"code":"BSAT-STR-2026-002","prefix":"STR","subsystem":"STRUCTURE & THERMAL CONTROL","title":"Thermal Design & Cold Environment Testing","skills":"Heat transfer, thermal modeling, insulation materials, experimental testing","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"The stratosphere is a thermal paradox: air at \u221260 \u00b0C but too thin to carry heat away effectively, full sun on one face and radiative cold sky on the other. Electronics generate their own heat, so a well-insulated box can stay comfortable inside \u2014 but batteries and external sensors need careful placement, and cameras need windows that do not frost over during descent through moist air. This project builds the thermal model of the payload (conduction through foam, internal convection, radiation) and validates it in a dry-ice cold chamber you construct yourself. The interplay with BSAT-AVI-2026-002 is tight: battery placement is a thermal decision. Start with a simple lumped-capacitance model of a foam box with a known heat source, then test it.","scope":"Keep electronics alive at \u221260 \u00b0C: insulation design, thermal mass placement, optional heater circuit sizing, thermal model of the payload interior, and validation in a dry-ice cold chamber you build yourself.","deliverables":["Thermal analysis report","DIY cold-test chamber","Validated thermal protection design"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-002, BSAT-PLC-2026-004, BSAT-STR-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-STR-2026-003","prefix":"STR","subsystem":"STRUCTURE & THERMAL CONTROL","title":"Recovery Hardware & Rigging","skills":"Structural design, load testing, materials selection, knots & rigging","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Between the balloon and the payload runs a chain of components that all experience the mission's most violent moment: burst, when drag loads spike and 1+ kg of shredded latex whips around the line. Every attachment point, knot, ring and cord in the load path is this project's responsibility, along with the radar reflector mounting required in many jurisdictions. The rules of thumb are aerospace ones: identify the load path, compute worst-case loads (burst shock, parachute opening, ground impact), then proof-test to 5\u00d7 \u2014 because a single failed knot loses the entire mission. Materials matter too: nylon goes brittle at \u221260 \u00b0C. Start by drawing the complete payload train and labeling the load at every junction.","scope":"Design all load-path hardware: attachment points, load rings, shock cord sizing, parachute connection, radar reflector mounting. Proof-load test everything to 5\u00d7 expected loads including burst shock loading.","deliverables":["Flight rigging kit","Proof-load test report","Rigging assembly procedure"],"linkages":["BSAT-MSN-2026-002, BSAT-STR-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-STR-2026-004","prefix":"STR","subsystem":"STRUCTURE & THERMAL CONTROL","title":"Environmental Test Program & Test Rigs","skills":"Test engineering, fixture design, instrumentation, documentation","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Real aerospace programs live by 'test like you fly' \u2014 every flight component proves itself in ground testing that mimics flight conditions. This project builds the program's test infrastructure and standards: a drop rig for impact, a shake test for launch handling and flight vibration, cold soak procedures, and a burn-in protocol. You define the pass/fail criteria and run every other team's hardware through acceptance testing before it earns a place on the payload \u2014 a quality-gate role that teaches test engineering, fixture design and disciplined documentation. The mindset shift is from 'it worked once' to 'it cannot fail'. Start by writing a one-page environmental test standard listing conditions the flight will impose, with numbers.","scope":"Build the test infrastructure for the whole program: drop-test rig, vibration/shake test setup, whip-test (for antenna/boom), and a vacuum test using a vacuum chamber if available. Define pass/fail criteria and run acceptance tests for every flying subsystem.","deliverables":["Test rigs (drop/vibe)","Environmental test standard document","Acceptance test reports for all subsystems"],"linkages":["All teams"]},{"code":"BSAT-STR-2026-005","prefix":"STR","subsystem":"STRUCTURE & THERMAL CONTROL","title":"Camera Mounts & External Booms","skills":"Mechanical design, vibration isolation, 3D printing, optics basics","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Cameras are the emotional payload of every BalloonSat \u2014 the shot of Earth's curve against black sky is what everyone remembers \u2014 but getting it is mechanical engineering. Mounts must hold cameras rigidly through vibration yet isolate them from payload resonances; lenses frost over during descent unless windows are treated or heated; and external sensor probes must sit on booms outside the payload's thermal boundary layer or they measure box temperature, not atmosphere. This project designs those mounts, booms and windows, working closely with the gimbal (BSAT-MEC-2026-002) and sensor (BSAT-AVI-2026-004) teams. Weight is the constant enemy. Start by testing anti-fog approaches in a freezer with a humid transition \u2014 the exact condition of descent through cloud.","scope":"Design vibration-isolated camera mounts (down-looking + horizon), external sensor booms that place probes outside the payload's thermal boundary layer, and lens anti-fog/anti-frost measures.","deliverables":["Camera mount assemblies","Sensor boom","Frost-prevention test results"],"linkages":["BSAT-MEC-2026-002, BSAT-AVI-2026-004, BSAT-AIM-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-MEC-2026-001","prefix":"MEC","subsystem":"MECHANISMS & ACTUATION","title":"Flight Termination / Cut-Down Mechanism","skills":"Actuator design, embedded control, FMEA, redundancy design","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"A cut-down device separates the payload from the balloon on command \u2014 the mission's emergency brake if the flight drifts toward an airport or the border. It is a beautiful mechatronics problem because the requirements conflict: it must fire with 100% certainty when commanded, yet never fire accidentally from vibration, cold, radio noise or a software glitch. The classic actuator is a nichrome hot-wire melting through the nylon line; alternatives are servo releases and pyrotechnic-free spring devices. The real deliverable is the failure-mode analysis (FMEA) and a large test log across temperatures \u2014 proving both that it fires and that it doesn't. Start by measuring how nichrome cut time varies from +25 \u00b0C to \u221260 \u00b0C.","scope":"Design a remotely-commanded and timer-backed cut-down device (nichrome hot-wire or servo release) that separates the payload from the balloon if it drifts toward no-fly zones. Include full failure-mode analysis \u2014 it must never trigger accidentally.","deliverables":["Flight-ready cut-down unit","FMEA document","20+ successful trigger test log"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-001, BSAT-MSN-2026-005, BSAT-SWS-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-MEC-2026-002","prefix":"MEC","subsystem":"MECHANISMS & ACTUATION","title":"Actively Stabilized Camera Platform","skills":"Control systems (PID), IMU sensor fusion, servo/gimbal hardware, embedded programming","difficulty":"Advanced  |  4 students","summary":"The payload spins and swings throughout ascent (see BSAT-MSN-2026-004), which ruins video and pointing-dependent experiments. This project fights back actively: a 1\u20132 axis gimbal that senses rotation with an IMU and counter-rotates the camera with servo or brushless motors. It is a complete closed-loop control project \u2014 sensor fusion to estimate attitude (complementary or Kalman filter), PID tuning, actuator saturation, and the special challenges of \u221260 \u00b0C operation where grease stiffens and servo plastics turn brittle. The final exam is unambiguous: side-by-side stabilized vs unstabilized flight footage. Start with a single-axis tabletop gimbal on a turntable and tune the loop until the horizon stays level.","scope":"Build a 1\u20132 axis camera stabilization system using IMU feedback and servo/brushless gimbal control to counteract payload spin, so video stays horizon-locked. Compare stabilized vs unstabilized footage from the flight.","deliverables":["Working gimbal unit","Control loop tuning report","Flight footage comparison"],"linkages":["BSAT-MSN-2026-004, BSAT-STR-2026-005, BSAT-AVI-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-MEC-2026-003","prefix":"MEC","subsystem":"MECHANISMS & ACTUATION","title":"Automated Antenna Tracking Rotator","skills":"Motor control, mechanical gearing, inverse pointing math, serial protocols (rotctl)","difficulty":"Advanced  |  4 students","summary":"A high-gain Yagi antenna hears the balloon 300 km away but only within its narrow beam \u2014 so someone must point it, continuously, for three hours, as the balloon crosses the sky. This project builds the machine that does it: a motorized azimuth/elevation rotator with enough torque for a 2 m antenna in wind, position feedback, limit switches, and backlash small enough to keep the beam on target. It pairs with BSAT-GND-2026-004 (the pointing software); your side is motors, gears, structure and the embedded controller speaking the standard rotctl protocol. Commercial rotators cost hundreds of dollars \u2014 yours should match them for a fraction. Start by computing required torque and pointing accuracy from the antenna's beamwidth (~30\u00b0 for a 7-element Yagi, so \u00b15\u00b0 is fine).","scope":"Build a motorized azimuth/elevation rotator that automatically points the ground-station Yagi at the balloon using live GPS telemetry. Stepper/DC motors, gearing, limit switches, and rotctl-compatible control software.","deliverables":["Working Az/El rotator with auto-tracking","Pointing accuracy test report"],"linkages":["BSAT-GND-2026-001, BSAT-GND-2026-004, BSAT-SWS-2026-002"]},{"code":"BSAT-MEC-2026-004","prefix":"MEC","subsystem":"MECHANISMS & ACTUATION","title":"Automated Air Sampling Mechanism","skills":"Actuators & valves, pneumatics basics, altitude-triggered control, sealing design","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"The chemistry-payload team wants pristine stratospheric air, and this project builds the robot arm of the mission: a sampling mechanism that opens sealed bags or canisters at programmed altitudes (e.g. 10, 20, 30 km), draws in ambient air, and reseals against contamination during descent through lower atmosphere. The mechatronics challenges stack up: valves and servos that actuate at \u221260 \u00b0C, altitude triggering from the flight computer, sample integrity verification, and doing it all within a tight mass budget. Contamination is the silent failure mode \u2014 a leaky seal gives the chemistry-payload team ground air and a worthless result, so seal testing is half the project. Start by defining the contamination requirements with the BSAT-PLC-2026-002 team, then prototype one valve-and-bag unit and vacuum-test its seal.","scope":"Design a servo-actuated air sampling system: sealed sample bags/canisters with valves that open at programmed altitudes (e.g. 10/20/30 km) and reseal, giving the chemistry-payload team uncontaminated stratospheric air samples.","deliverables":["3-altitude sampling mechanism","Seal integrity test report","Altitude trigger firmware"],"linkages":["BSAT-PLC-2026-002, BSAT-AVI-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-MEC-2026-005","prefix":"MEC","subsystem":"MECHANISMS & ACTUATION","title":"Smart Recovery Aids Package","skills":"Landing detection algorithms, low-power actuation, embedded sensors","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Statistically, finding the payload is the hardest part of a balloon mission \u2014 GPS gets you to within ~10 metres, but the last 50 metres in a sugarcane field or forest can take hours. This project builds the payload's self-rescue kit: landing detection logic (GPS descent-rate plus accelerometer impact signature), then automatic activation of a high-brightness strobe, a piercing piezo siren, and optionally a servo-raised flag or antenna mast to lift the radio above the crop canopy. The interesting engineering is the landing detector \u2014 it must never trigger in flight, yet always trigger on landing, on battery power that must last many hours of searching. Start by recording accelerometer data from drop tests and designing a robust landing signature.","scope":"Build the post-landing recovery suite: high-brightness LED strobe, loud piezo siren, servo-deployed flag/antenna raiser (payloads land in crops/trees), all activated automatically by landing detection logic (GPS + accelerometer).","deliverables":["Recovery aids module","Landing-detection algorithm validation","Field find-test results"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-005, Recovery team"]},{"code":"BSAT-DHA-2026-001","prefix":"DHA","subsystem":"DATA HANDLING & ANALYTICS","title":"Real-Time Telemetry Pipeline & Dashboard","skills":"Python, time-series DB (InfluxDB/TimescaleDB), Grafana/Plotly Dash, data pipelines","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"During flight, telemetry packets arrive every few seconds carrying position, temperatures, battery voltage and science data \u2014 and mission control needs to see it as live, trustworthy visualizations, not scrolling text. This project builds the real-time data backbone: ingesting decoded packets, storing them in a time-series database, and serving a dashboard with altitude profiles, sensor graphs, packet-loss statistics and data-quality flags. The engineering challenges are real-world data ones: out-of-order and corrupted packets, duplicates from multiple receiver stations, and graceful behavior during radio dropouts. On launch day your dashboard is the room's single source of truth. Start by defining the packet schema with BSAT-SWS-2026-004 and replaying recorded telemetry from past public HAB flights through your pipeline.","scope":"Build the live data pipeline: ingest decoded packets from the ground station, store in a time-series database, and serve a live dashboard with altitude/temperature/battery graphs, packet statistics and data quality indicators during flight.","deliverables":["Live telemetry dashboard","Pipeline architecture doc","Launch-day data ops runbook"],"linkages":["BSAT-SWS-2026-002, BSAT-SWS-2026-003, BSAT-GND-2026-005"]},{"code":"BSAT-DHA-2026-002","prefix":"DHA","subsystem":"DATA HANDLING & ANALYTICS","title":"Atmospheric Data Analysis & Science Report","skills":"Pandas/NumPy, statistics, atmospheric science basics, scientific writing","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"A balloon flight is a physics experiment that hands you a beautiful dataset: pressure falling exponentially through two decades, temperature dropping to \u221260 \u00b0C then rising again above the tropopause \u2014 the signature of the ozone layer's heating. This project turns raw flight data into science: cleaning and synchronizing multi-sensor time series, reconstructing altitude from both GPS and pressure (they disagree \u2014 understanding why is half the lesson), identifying the tropopause, and comparing everything against the ISA standard atmosphere and same-day radiosonde soundings from your national weather service. It is a complete, honest data-analysis project with uncertainty quantification on real, imperfect data. Start by analyzing a published radiosonde dataset so your pipeline is ready before your flight data exists.","scope":"Post-flight, analyze the full dataset: temperature/pressure/humidity profiles vs altitude, identify the tropopause, compare against ISA standard atmosphere and same-day radiosonde/weather-model data, quantify sensor errors.","deliverables":["Published flight dataset (cleaned)","Atmospheric analysis report","Comparison vs reference data"],"linkages":["BSAT-PLD-2026-002, BSAT-AVI-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-DHA-2026-003","prefix":"DHA","subsystem":"DATA HANDLING & ANALYTICS","title":"Landing Zone Prediction Model","skills":"Monte Carlo methods, GFS/wind data APIs, geospatial analysis (GeoPandas), ML regression","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"Where will it land? \u2014 the question every chase team asks, and pure physics gives an incomplete answer because burst altitude, descent rate and winds are all uncertain. This project treats landing prediction as a probabilistic problem: Monte Carlo simulation sampling over those uncertainties, driven by GFS wind forecasts, producing not a point but a probability ellipse on a map. During flight it gets more interesting \u2014 each new telemetry packet lets you re-run the prediction with actual measured winds, shrinking the ellipse in real time for the chase team. Geospatial data science with immediate, visceral validation: you end the day standing where your model said to stand. Start by wiring up GFS data access and simulating descent trajectories from a fixed burst point.","scope":"Build a statistical/ML landing-point predictor using wind forecast data (GFS), Monte Carlo simulation over uncertain burst altitude and descent rates. Output a landing probability ellipse map; validate against the real landing spot.","deliverables":["Landing prediction tool with probability map","Validation report vs actual flight"],"linkages":["BSAT-MSN-2026-001, Recovery team"]},{"code":"BSAT-DHA-2026-004","prefix":"DHA","subsystem":"DATA HANDLING & ANALYTICS","title":"Telemetry Anomaly & Health Monitoring","skills":"Statistical process control, anomaly detection, alerting systems, Python","difficulty":"Medium  |  2 students","summary":"Sensors fail quietly: a battery voltage sags slightly faster than it should, an external thermistor reads suspiciously like the internal one, GPS altitude stalls while pressure keeps falling. During a mission nobody has time to stare at raw numbers, so this project builds automated health monitoring: statistical rules and change-point detection over live telemetry streams, raising prioritized alerts in mission control ('battery trend predicts depletion before landing'). Post-flight, the same system generates an anomaly timeline for every subsystem team. It teaches the applied statistics of streaming data \u2014 baselines, drift, false-alarm trade-offs \u2014 on a system where a missed alarm costs the mission. Start by injecting synthetic faults into replayed telemetry and measuring your detection and false-alarm rates.","scope":"Define health rules and statistical anomaly detection for live telemetry (battery droop, temperature runaway, GPS dropout, sensor drift). Alert mission control in real time and auto-generate a post-flight anomaly timeline.","deliverables":["Live health-monitoring module with alerts","Post-flight anomaly report"],"linkages":["BSAT-DHA-2026-001, BSAT-SWS-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-DHA-2026-005","prefix":"DHA","subsystem":"DATA HANDLING & ANALYTICS","title":"Flight Data Portal & Public Outreach Analytics","skills":"Web visualization (Plotly/D3/CesiumJS), data publishing, storytelling with data","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"A balloon mission generates the most shareable content a college program can produce \u2014 near-space photos, a 3D flight path, dramatic data \u2014 and this project makes it public. Build the program's open-data portal: cleaned datasets with documentation, interactive visualizations (3D flight replay over terrain, altitude-synced photo browser, sensor explorers), and content feeds for the website and social media. There is real data engineering underneath \u2014 reproducible processing from raw logs to published data, versioning, metadata standards \u2014 plus the storytelling craft of making a temperature profile compelling to a non-scientist. Your work is also the program's face to sponsors and future students. Start by studying how public agencies publish mission data and designing your dataset schema before the flight.","scope":"Build the program's public face: an open data portal hosting all flight datasets with interactive visualizations (3D flight path, altitude profiles, photo map), plus outreach analytics. Feeds the college website/social media.","deliverables":["Public flight-data portal","Interactive 3d flight replay","Outreach content pack"],"linkages":["BSAT-DHA-2026-001, BSAT-SWS-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLD-2026-001","prefix":"PLD","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 ATMOSPHERIC PHYSICS","title":"Cosmic Ray Flux vs Altitude Experiment","skills":"Radiation detection, detector calibration, counting statistics, data analysis","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"At ground level, the atmosphere shields us from most cosmic radiation \u2014 but a balloon climbs through the shield. Count rates rise with altitude to a maximum around 15\u201320 km (the Regener\u2013Pfotzer maximum, where primary cosmic rays shower into secondaries faster than the thinning air absorbs them) and then fall again, a discovery that originally came from balloon flights and helped prove cosmic rays were extraterrestrial. This project repeats that classic experiment: fly a Geiger\u2013M\u00fcller tube or scintillator, handle counting statistics correctly (counts are Poisson \u2014 plan integration times), calibrate on the ground, and shield against the payload's own electronics noise. Your data should clearly show the maximum. Start by characterizing your detector's background rate and dead time in the lab.","scope":"Fly a Geiger\u2013M\u00fcller counter (or SiPM+scintillator) to measure ionizing radiation count rate from ground to 30+ km, capturing the Regener\u2013Pfotzer maximum (~15\u201320 km). Calibrate on the ground with known sources; analyze count rate vs altitude/pressure.","deliverables":["Flight-ready radiation detector","Calibration report","Cosmic ray flux vs altitude paper"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-001, BSAT-DHA-2026-002"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLD-2026-002","prefix":"PLD","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 ATMOSPHERIC PHYSICS","title":"Stratospheric Atmospheric Profiling","skills":"Thermodynamics, instrumentation, error analysis, atmospheric physics","difficulty":"Medium  |  2 students","summary":"Measuring air temperature from a moving balloon sounds trivial and is anything but: a sensor in sunlight reads radiative heating, not air temperature; a sensor with slow response smears the profile across hundreds of metres of ascent; a sensor near the payload measures the box's thermal wake. Professional radiosondes solve these with tiny shielded, aspirated sensors \u2014 this project re-derives that engineering: sensor time-constant characterization, radiation shielding, boom placement (with BSAT-STR-2026-005), and altitude reconstruction reconciling GPS with pressure-integrated altitude. Done well, your profile through the tropopause matches the professional soundings; done carelessly, errors of 5\u201310 \u00b0C are typical. Start by measuring your sensor's time constant with a step-change experiment and computing the smearing at 5 m/s ascent.","scope":"Design the precision atmospheric measurement experiment: response-time-corrected temperature probes (radiation-shielded, on a boom), pressure-derived vs GPS altitude comparison, lapse rate and tropopause characterization.","deliverables":["Shielded probe assembly","Altitude reconstruction methodology","Atmospheric profile analysis"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-004, BSAT-STR-2026-005, BSAT-DHA-2026-002"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLD-2026-003","prefix":"PLD","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 ATMOSPHERIC PHYSICS","title":"UV & Solar Irradiance vs Altitude","skills":"Radiometry, optical sensor calibration, photometry, ozone physics","difficulty":"Medium  |  2 students","summary":"The ozone layer absorbs most solar UV-B before it reaches the ground \u2014 and your balloon flies up through the absorbing layer, so UV intensity climbs dramatically with altitude, far faster than total sunlight does. This project quantifies that: calibrated UV-A and UV-B sensors plus a total-irradiance reference, flown with known orientation (or corrected using IMU data, since a swinging payload changes the sun angle constantly). The analysis connects measured attenuation to the Beer\u2013Lambert law and the overhead ozone column, tying directly into the ozone payload project (BSAT-PLC-2026-001). Careful radiometry \u2014 cosine response, temperature coefficients, cross-sensitivity to visible light \u2014 separates good results from noise. Start by cross-calibrating your sensors against a reference on clear days at fixed sun angles.","scope":"Measure UV-A/UV-B and total solar irradiance through the flight to quantify ozone-layer attenuation. Calibrate sensors against reference measurements; analyze irradiance vs altitude and solar angle, and estimate ozone column effects.","deliverables":["Calibrated UV payload","Irradiance vs altitude analysis","Ozone attenuation report"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-004, BSAT-PLC-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLD-2026-004","prefix":"PLD","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 ATMOSPHERIC PHYSICS","title":"Geomagnetic Field Mapping Experiment","skills":"Magnetometry, sensor fusion, hard/soft iron calibration, IGRF model","difficulty":"Medium  |  2 students","summary":"Earth's magnetic field is mapped globally by the IGRF model \u2014 and your balloon gives you a 30 km vertical transect to test it against. The physics is subtle in a good way: the field changes only ~1% over the altitude range, so this is precision measurement, and the raw magnetometer data is contaminated by the payload itself (hard-iron offsets from magnets and currents, soft-iron distortion from steel) and scrambled by payload rotation. Recovering the true field vector requires calibration ellipsoid fitting and sensor fusion with the IMU \u2014 the exact techniques used on real spacecraft magnetometer booms. Agreement with IGRF within a few hundred nanotesla is an excellent result. Start with hard/soft-iron calibration on the ground, rotating the assembled payload, not the bare sensor.","scope":"Fly a calibrated 3-axis magnetometer to profile Earth's magnetic field vs altitude and position. Handle payload rotation (fusion with IMU), remove hard/soft-iron effects from the payload itself, compare against IGRF model predictions.","deliverables":["Calibrated magnetometer package","Field-vs-igrf comparison analysis"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-004, BSAT-MSN-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLD-2026-005","prefix":"PLD","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 ATMOSPHERIC PHYSICS","title":"Near-Space Optical Phenomena Study","skills":"Optics, image analysis, Rayleigh scattering theory, camera calibration","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Why is the sky blue, and why does it stop being blue? A balloon camera watches Rayleigh scattering disappear in real time: as air thins, the sky overhead darkens toward black while a bright blue rim hugs the horizon. This project does quantitative optics on flight imagery: measuring sky brightness vs altitude from calibrated images (requiring control of camera exposure and response), and the classic exercise of estimating Earth's radius from the horizon's curvature \u2014 which demands honest treatment of lens distortion, refraction and the difference between the true and apparent horizon. It is the most accessible physics project and produces the most beautiful figures. Start by calibrating your camera's lens distortion with a checkerboard and locking its exposure settings.","scope":"Use flight imagery scientifically: measure sky darkening vs altitude (Rayleigh scattering), estimate Earth's radius from horizon curvature photos (correcting lens distortion), and analyze the black-sky/blue-limb transition.","deliverables":["Camera calibration procedure","Earth-radius estimate from flight images","Scattering analysis report"],"linkages":["BSAT-STR-2026-005, BSAT-AIM-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLC-2026-001","prefix":"PLC","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 CHEMISTRY & MATERIALS","title":"Ozone Concentration Profiling","skills":"Electrochemical sensors, gas calibration, cross-sensitivity analysis, atmospheric chemistry","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"Ozone is a trace gas \u2014 parts per million even in the ozone layer \u2014 yet it shapes the entire temperature structure of the stratosphere and shields the biosphere from UV. Professional ozonesondes measure it with electrochemical cells flown on weather balloons; this project attempts the same measurement with student-accessible sensors, which is honestly hard: low-cost electrochemical and metal-oxide ozone sensors have strong temperature and pressure dependencies and cross-sensitivities that swamp the signal unless carefully characterized. The project is therefore mostly analytical chemistry on the ground \u2014 calibration against known ozone concentrations, compensation model development \u2014 with the flight as the final exam. Compare your profile's shape against published ozonesonde data. Start by building an ozone calibration setup with a small UV-lamp ozone generator.","scope":"Fly electrochemical/MOS ozone sensors to profile O\u2083 concentration vs altitude. Major challenge: calibrating low-cost sensors and compensating for temperature/pressure effects. Compare against published ozonesonde profiles.","deliverables":["Calibrated ozone payload","T/P compensation methodology","Ozone profile report"],"linkages":["BSAT-PLD-2026-003, BSAT-AVI-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLC-2026-002","prefix":"PLC","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 CHEMISTRY & MATERIALS","title":"Stratospheric Air Sampling & Lab Analysis","skills":"Analytical chemistry, GC/GC-MS, sampling protocols, contamination control","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"What is stratospheric air actually made of? Well-mixed gases like CO\u2082 and CH\u2084 stay near-constant with altitude, water vapor collapses to a few parts per million, and ozone appears \u2014 and with the BSAT-MEC-2026-004 sampling mechanism, you can bring samples home and find out. This project owns everything analytical: a contamination-free sampling protocol (the payload's own outgassing plastics are a contamination source), sample bag/canister material selection, chain-of-custody handling, and lab analysis by GC or GC-MS comparing composition across three altitudes and ground air. The honest challenge is that samples are small and contamination risks are everywhere \u2014 rigorous blanks and controls make or break the result. Start by analyzing ground air reproducibly, then vacuum-test the sample containers for storage stability.","scope":"Analyze air samples captured by the BSAT-MEC-2026-004 mechanism: design contamination-free sampling protocol, then lab analysis (GC/GC-MS if available) for CO\u2082/CH\u2084/trace gases; compare compositions at 3 altitudes vs ground air.","deliverables":["Sampling protocol document","Lab analysis results","Altitude composition comparison report"],"linkages":[]},{"code":"BSAT-PLC-2026-003","prefix":"PLC","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 CHEMISTRY & MATERIALS","title":"Aerosol & Particulate Collection Study","skills":"Aerosol science, microscopy (optical/SEM if available), filter chemistry","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"The stratosphere carries a thin haze of aerosols \u2014 sulfate particles from volcanic eruptions, meteoric dust, desert dust lofted by storms, and (controversially) viable microbes have all been reported by balloon sampling campaigns. This project builds simple collectors \u2014 impaction plates and filters exposed at altitude by a shuttered mechanism \u2014 and does the post-flight forensics: optical and (if available) electron microscopy, particle counting and sizing, and elemental analysis to guess at origins. Contamination control is the defining discipline: a fingerprint or launch-field dust ruins everything, so sterile preparation, sealed exposure control samples and blind analysis are essential. Start by exposing collectors at ground level and building your particle-identification skills on known dusts.","scope":"Design passive/active particulate collectors (impaction plates, filters) to capture aerosols at altitude; post-flight microscopy and chemical analysis of collected particles; investigate possible stratospheric microbial/dust capture.","deliverables":["Collector hardware","Particle analysis report with imagery","Contamination-control assessment"],"linkages":["BSAT-STR-2026-001, BSAT-MEC-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLC-2026-004","prefix":"PLC","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 CHEMISTRY & MATERIALS","title":"Battery Chemistry Performance in Extreme Cold","skills":"Electrochemistry, battery testing, cold-chamber experimentation, data analysis","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Every battery datasheet shows capacity at 25 \u00b0C; your mission runs at \u221240 \u00b0C and colder, where electrolyte viscosity rises, ion mobility falls, and internal resistance can multiply five-fold. This project is systematic electrochemistry with a mission-critical customer: characterize candidate chemistries (Li-FeS\u2082 primary, Li-SOCl\u2082, Li-ion, NiMH, alkaline) across temperature \u2014 capacity retention, voltage under load, internal resistance via pulse testing \u2014 in a dry-ice cold chamber. The physical chemistry is rich (Arrhenius behavior of rate processes, Peukert effects) and the output is direct: your data selects the flight battery for BSAT-AVI-2026-002. Lithium primary cells famously dominate HAB flights; your job is to show why, quantitatively. Start by building a constant-current discharge rig with logging, then validate it at room temperature.","scope":"Systematic study of battery chemistries (Li-SOCl\u2082, Li-FeS\u2082/Energizer Lithium, Li-ion, NiMH, alkaline) at \u221260 to +25 \u00b0C: capacity, voltage sag, internal resistance vs temperature. Directly drives BSAT-AVI-2026-002's battery selection.","deliverables":["Battery performance database vs temperature","Recommendation report for flight battery"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-002, BSAT-STR-2026-002"]},{"code":"BSAT-PLC-2026-005","prefix":"PLC","subsystem":"SCIENCE PAYLOAD \u2013 CHEMISTRY & MATERIALS","title":"Materials Degradation in Near-Space Conditions","skills":"Polymer chemistry, materials characterization (FTIR/UV-Vis), experimental design","difficulty":"Medium  |  2 students","summary":"Materials that behave at room temperature turn treacherous in near-space: PLA prints go glassy and crack at \u221260 \u00b0C, adhesives embrittle, plasticizers stiffen, and unfiltered UV at altitude is harsher than anything at ground level. This project flies a coupon board \u2014 small standardized samples of polymers, adhesives, coatings and 3D-print filaments \u2014 exposed to the full flight environment, with an identical control set kept on the ground. Pre- and post-flight characterization (FTIR for chemical changes, tensile or flex tests for mechanical ones, colorimetry for UV damage) turns anecdotes into a materials selection guide future missions will actually use. One flight is a short exposure, so sensitivity of your characterization methods matters. Start by testing your candidate materials in a freezer and under a UV lamp to rehearse the analysis.","scope":"Fly a coupon board of materials (polymers, adhesives, coatings, 3D-print filaments) exposed to UV + cold + low pressure; pre/post characterization (FTIR, tensile, visual) to build a materials selection guide for future missions.","deliverables":["Exposed coupon experiment","Pre/post analysis report","Materials selection guide"],"linkages":["BSAT-STR-2026-001, BSAT-PLD-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-SWS-2026-001","prefix":"SWS","subsystem":"FLIGHT & GROUND SOFTWARE","title":"Flight Software & Onboard Data System","skills":"Embedded C/C++, RTOS or superloop design, state machines, fault-tolerant design, Git","difficulty":"Advanced  |  4 students","summary":"Flight software is where computer science meets consequences: once released, no one can restart the program for three hours, and every bug flies with you. The architecture is a mission state machine \u2014 pre-launch, ascent, burst, descent, landed \u2014 because correct behavior differs by phase (transmit fast during descent for recovery; save power after landing). Around it: sensor polling with per-device fault isolation (one frozen I2C sensor must not hang the loop), dual-redundant logging, watchdog-supervised recovery from crashes, and defensive handling of every 'impossible' input. The testing culture is the real lesson \u2014 fault injection, 24-hour burn-ins, and code review as if lives depended on it. Start by writing the state machine and its transition rules on paper before any code, then build the fault-injection harness alongside the firmware.","scope":"Write the mission-critical flight firmware: state machine (pre-launch/ascent/burst/descent/landed), sensor polling, dual logging (SD + flash), telemetry packet generation, watchdog recovery, safe-mode behavior. Extensive fault-injection testing.","deliverables":["Flight firmware (tested via fault injection)","Software design document","24-hour burn-in test log"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-001, BSAT-AVI-2026-004, BSAT-SWS-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-SWS-2026-002","prefix":"SWS","subsystem":"FLIGHT & GROUND SOFTWARE","title":"Ground Station Receiver Software","skills":"Python/C++, serial & SDR interfaces, packet parsing, databases, networking","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Radio hands you a stream of bytes that are sometimes wrong, sometimes duplicated, sometimes missing \u2014 turning that into clean mission data is the ground software's job. This project builds the receive-side pipeline: interfacing to LoRa modules and SDR decoders, validating packet CRCs, parsing the binary format into structured records, archiving everything (raw and decoded \u2014 you will re-analyze later), and serving a network API that mission control and the dashboard consume. The elegant subproblem is multi-station merging: several receivers hear the same flight with different gaps, and combining their logs recovers packets no single station caught. Reliability engineering matters \u2014 this software must run for hours unattended on launch day. Start by defining the packet spec with BSAT-SWS-2026-004 and testing with deliberately corrupted packets.","scope":"Build the receive chain software: interface to LoRa receiver/SDR, packet decoding, CRC validation, decoded-packet database logging, and a network API that feeds mission control and the dashboard. Include multi-station packet merging.","deliverables":["Ground decoding software suite","Multi-station merge tool","Decoded packet archive from flight"],"linkages":["BSAT-GND-2026-003, BSAT-GND-2026-005, BSAT-DHA-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-SWS-2026-003","prefix":"SWS","subsystem":"FLIGHT & GROUND SOFTWARE","title":"Mission Control Web Application","skills":"Full-stack web (React/Vue + backend), WebSockets, mapping APIs (Leaflet), mobile-responsive design","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Mission control is a software product with the hardest kind of user: stressed people making time-critical decisions. This project builds the web application the whole program watches on launch day \u2014 live map with the balloon's track and predicted landing zone, real-time telemetry graphs, a go/no-go checklist tool for launch procedures, an event log, and a mobile view for the chase team navigating farm roads toward the landing point. The technical stack is modern full-web (WebSockets for live data, mapping libraries, responsive design), but the differentiating skill is UX under pressure: information hierarchy, glanceability, and graceful behavior when the data feed drops. Start by storyboarding launch day minute-by-minute and designing screens for each phase before writing code.","scope":"Build the mission control system: live map with balloon position + predicted path, telemetry graphs, go/no-go checklist module, event log, chase-team mobile view with navigation to live/predicted landing point.","deliverables":["Deployed mission control web app","Chase-team mobile view","Launch-day usage report"],"linkages":["BSAT-SWS-2026-002, BSAT-DHA-2026-001, BSAT-DHA-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-SWS-2026-004","prefix":"SWS","subsystem":"FLIGHT & GROUND SOFTWARE","title":"Telemetry Protocol & Error Correction Design","skills":"Communication protocols, coding theory (FEC), binary serialization, simulation testing","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"Every byte transmitted from the balloon costs airtime, battery and regulatory duty-cycle allowance \u2014 so the telemetry protocol is an exercise in engineering under scarcity. This project designs the mission's language: a compact binary packet format (bit-packed fields, not JSON), CRC integrity checks, forward error correction (Reed\u2013Solomon, as used by deep-space missions) so corrupted packets can be repaired rather than discarded, and priority scheduling that guarantees position packets even when science data queues up. The theory is real computer science \u2014 information theory, coding theory, serialization \u2014 validated by a packet-loss simulator that injects errors and measures recovered throughput. Your specification document becomes law for three other teams. Start by computing your true channel budget: bytes per minute within duty-cycle limits.","scope":"Design the radio protocol: compact binary packet format, CRC + forward error correction (Reed-Solomon/convolutional), priority scheduling (position > science data), retransmission strategy, bandwidth budgeting. Test under simulated packet loss.","deliverables":["Protocol specification document","Encoder/decoder libraries (flight + ground)","Loss-tolerance test report"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-003, BSAT-SWS-2026-001, BSAT-SWS-2026-002"]},{"code":"BSAT-SWS-2026-005","prefix":"SWS","subsystem":"FLIGHT & GROUND SOFTWARE","title":"Recovery & Chase Coordination App","skills":"Mobile/PWA development, offline-first design, geolocation, SMS gateway integration","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Recovery is a software problem disguised as a hike: the chase team is in a car with patchy internet, trying to converge on a moving prediction, then searching a field for a white box. This project builds their toolkit as an offline-first mobile app/PWA: cached maps for rural dead zones, live and last-known balloon positions, the BSAT-DHA-2026-003 landing ellipse, team member location sharing, navigation to the target, and a direction-finding mode that visualizes LoRa signal strength as you walk. It also integrates the BSAT-AVI-2026-005 backup tracker's SMS positions \u2014 parsing texts into map pins automatically. Offline-first architecture is the core discipline: every feature must degrade gracefully without connectivity. Start by mapping the recovery workflow end-to-end, then build the offline map caching first \u2014 everything else layers on it.","scope":"Build the recovery toolkit: mobile app/PWA showing last-known + predicted position, offline maps for rural areas, direction-finding helper (signal strength display), team location sharing, and integration of the GSM backup tracker's SMS positions.","deliverables":["Chase app with offline maps","SMS tracker integration","Field trial report"],"linkages":["BSAT-AVI-2026-005, BSAT-DHA-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-AIM-2026-001","prefix":"AIM","subsystem":"AI / ML & ONBOARD INTELLIGENCE","title":"Onboard Edge-AI Image Classification","skills":"TensorFlow Lite/ONNX, model quantization, embedded Linux, power-constrained inference","difficulty":"Advanced  |  4 students","summary":"The radio downlink is a soda straw \u2014 kilobytes per minute \u2014 while the onboard camera fills gigabytes. The modern answer is edge AI: run a lightweight neural network on the payload itself to decide which images matter. This project deploys a quantized CNN on a Raspberry Pi (or similar) inside the payload to classify frames \u2014 cloud structures, clear ground views, horizon shots \u2014 and downlink only tiny thumbnails of the best, effectively giving mission control eyes during flight. The constraints are the interesting part: a few watts of power budget shared with heaters, cold effects on the compute module, and model compression (TFLite/ONNX quantization) to hit inference-per-second targets. Start by collecting training data from public HAB flight footage and benchmarking model families on your target hardware.","scope":"Deploy a lightweight CNN on a Raspberry Pi/edge device in the payload to classify images in-flight (cloud types, ground vs sky, interesting scenes) and prioritize which thumbnails to downlink over the slow radio channel.","deliverables":["Onboard inference system","Model accuracy report","Smart-downlink flight demonstration"],"linkages":["BSAT-STR-2026-005, BSAT-AVI-2026-003, BSAT-SWS-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-AIM-2026-002","prefix":"AIM","subsystem":"AI / ML & ONBOARD INTELLIGENCE","title":"ML-Enhanced Flight Path Prediction","skills":"scikit-learn/XGBoost, time-series ML, feature engineering with weather data, model evaluation","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"Physics-based flight predictors (BSAT-MSN-2026-001) rest on simplifying assumptions \u2014 constant drag coefficient, manufacturer burst diameter, smooth wind interpolation \u2014 and systematically miss in ways ML can learn. This project mines the thousands of publicly logged amateur HAB flights plus archived weather data to train models that predict burst altitude and refine landing zones, then benchmarks honestly against the physics baseline on held-out flights. It is a disciplined applied-ML project: feature engineering from weather fields, leakage-free validation (you cannot train on flights from the day you are predicting), uncertainty quantification, and the humility to report if physics wins. The deliverable includes a live prediction API for mission control. Start by scraping and cleaning historical flight logs \u2014 the dataset is the project's real asset.","scope":"Train ML models (gradient boosting/LSTM) on historical HAB flight data + weather archives to predict burst altitude and improve landing prediction beyond physics-only models. Quantify improvement vs the BSAT-MSN-2026-001/BSAT-DHA-2026-003 baseline.","deliverables":["Trained prediction models","Benchmark vs physics baseline","Prediction api for mission control"],"linkages":["BSAT-MSN-2026-001, BSAT-DHA-2026-003"]},{"code":"BSAT-AIM-2026-003","prefix":"AIM","subsystem":"AI / ML & ONBOARD INTELLIGENCE","title":"Computer Vision Post-Flight Analysis","skills":"OpenCV, feature detection, image stitching, georegistration, Python","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"A flight returns thousands of images tied to a GPS track \u2014 a natural computer-vision dataset with ground truth attached. This project builds the post-flight CV toolkit: automatic horizon detection (a surprisingly deep problem when the horizon is a fuzzy atmospheric gradient), altitude estimation from image features validated against GPS, stitching rotating-payload frames into panoramas, and georegistration \u2014 matching flight photos onto satellite imagery to determine exactly what the camera saw. Each task is classical CV (edge detection, feature matching, homographies) with modern options (learned features) available for comparison. The altitude-from-images study is genuinely novel territory for a student project. Start with OpenCV horizon detection on public HAB footage so the pipeline is ready before your flight.","scope":"Apply CV to flight imagery: automatic horizon detection, altitude estimation from image features, image stitching into panoramas, GPS-photo georegistration onto satellite maps, and automatic best-photo selection.","deliverables":["CV analysis toolkit","Georegistered photo map","Altitude-from-image validation study"],"linkages":["BSAT-PLD-2026-005, BSAT-STR-2026-005"]},{"code":"BSAT-AIM-2026-004","prefix":"AIM","subsystem":"AI / ML & ONBOARD INTELLIGENCE","title":"ML Anomaly Detection on Telemetry Streams","skills":"Unsupervised ML, autoencoders, streaming inference, synthetic data generation","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Rule-based health monitoring (BSAT-DHA-2026-004) catches failures someone anticipated; ML anomaly detection catches the ones nobody did. This project trains unsupervised models \u2014 autoencoders that learn to reconstruct 'normal' telemetry and flag what they cannot, isolation forests for point anomalies \u2014 on simulated and replayed flight data, then runs live during the mission alongside the rule-based system in a head-to-head comparison. The honest challenges are the ML-engineering ones: almost no labeled anomalies exist, so you must generate realistic synthetic faults; a balloon flight is inherently non-stationary (everything changes with altitude), so 'normal' is a moving target; and false alarms erode trust fast. Producing a labeled anomaly dataset for future teams is a lasting contribution. Start by building the synthetic fault injector \u2014 it is your training-data factory.","scope":"Go beyond rule-based monitoring: train autoencoder/isolation-forest models on simulated + real telemetry to detect subtle anomalies (slow sensor drift, unusual dynamics). Run live during flight alongside BSAT-DHA-2026-004 and compare detection performance.","deliverables":["ML anomaly detection service","Rule-based vs ml comparison study","Labeled anomaly dataset"],"linkages":["BSAT-DHA-2026-004, BSAT-DHA-2026-001"]},{"code":"BSAT-AIM-2026-005","prefix":"AIM","subsystem":"AI / ML & ONBOARD INTELLIGENCE","title":"AI-Assisted Signal Decoding & Denoising","skills":"DSP fundamentals, deep learning for signals (CNN/RNN on IQ data), SDR recording, PyTorch","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"When the balloon is 300 km out and the signal fades into noise, classical decoders simply reject corrupted packets \u2014 but the information is not entirely gone, and machine learning can sometimes claw it back. This research-flavored project records raw IQ samples (the complex baseband signal) at the SDR during flight, augments clean recordings with realistic synthetic noise and fading to build training data, and trains neural networks (CNNs/RNNs on IQ sequences) to denoise signals or classify symbols below the threshold where conventional demodulation fails. Post-flight, the model attempts recovery of the real packets lost at maximum range \u2014 a measurable, honest benchmark. It requires learning DSP fundamentals alongside deep learning, a genuinely valuable combination. Start by recording your own transmitter at controlled SNR levels and reproducing a classical demodulator in Python first.","scope":"Research project: use ML to recover weak/corrupted radio packets that classical decoding rejects \u2014 train denoising models on recorded IQ samples with synthetic noise, and attempt recovery of packets lost during the real flight.","deliverables":["IQ dataset with noise augmentation","Trained denoising model","Packet recovery rate study"],"linkages":["BSAT-GND-2026-003, BSAT-SWS-2026-004"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-001","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"High-Gain Yagi Antenna Design & Build","skills":"Antenna theory, 4NEC2/MMANA-GAL simulation, RF construction, SWR/NanoVNA measurement","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"The Yagi-Uda antenna \u2014 a driven dipole plus parasitic reflector and director elements \u2014 is how a ground station reaches out 300 km to a milliwatt transmitter: each added director focuses more energy into a narrower beam, trading coverage for gain. This project takes the full RF engineering journey: simulate the design (element lengths and spacing are sensitive at the millimetre level at 433 MHz), build it from aluminum tube or PCB, then measure reality \u2014 SWR with a NanoVNA, radiation pattern on an improvised antenna range \u2014 and reconcile simulation with measurement. Matching, balun design and weatherproofing complete the craft. Your antenna becomes the station's main aperture, mounted on the BSAT-MEC-2026-003 rotator. Start in simulation software and study why classic published designs choose 7\u201310 elements.","scope":"Design, simulate, build and tune a 433 MHz Yagi-Uda antenna (7\u201310 elements, ~11\u201313 dBi) for the main tracking station. Simulate in software, build from aluminum tube/PCB, measure SWR and radiation pattern, weatherproof it and mount on the rotator.","deliverables":["Tuned Yagi antenna","Simulation vs measured pattern report","Mounting hardware"],"linkages":["Avionics, Science Payload"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-002","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"Omnidirectional & Backup Antennas","skills":"Antenna fundamentals, coax/connector work, impedance matching, portable RF design","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"Not every antenna should be high-gain: when the balloon is overhead, a Yagi pointing at the horizon misses it entirely, and when the chase team is walking through a field, nobody carries a 2-metre boom. This project builds the supporting antenna cast: a quarter-wave ground-plane omni for reliable all-direction coverage near the station, possibly a collinear for more omni gain, a lightweight wire antenna for the payload itself, and the classic tape-measure Yagi \u2014 foldable, nearly indestructible \u2014 for handheld direction-finding in the final metres of recovery. Each teaches a different antenna principle, and comparative testing against BSAT-GND-2026-001's Yagi makes the gain/coverage trade-off concrete. Start with the ground-plane omni: one afternoon to build, and it becomes your reference antenna.","scope":"Build the secondary receive antennas: quarter-wave ground plane and/or collinear omni for 360\u00b0 coverage near the station, plus a lightweight airborne antenna for the payload, and a handheld tape-measure Yagi for direction-finding during recovery.","deliverables":["Ground-plane omni","Handheld df yagi","Airborne antenna","Comparison test report"],"linkages":["Avionics, Science Payload"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-003","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"SDR Receive Chain & RF Front-End","skills":"Software-defined radio, GNU Radio/SDR software, LNA/filter selection, RF measurements","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Software-defined radio replaces racks of analog equipment with a $30 dongle and code \u2014 the entire receiver (filtering, demodulation, decoding) becomes software you can inspect and improve. This project builds the station's receive chain: RTL-SDR or similar, a low-noise amplifier mounted at the antenna (the first amplifier sets the noise figure of everything after it \u2014 the Friis cascade formula makes this rigorous), a band-pass filter to keep strong local FM/GSM signals from overloading the front end, and the decoding stack for LoRa and other HAB modes. Quantifying sensitivity improvement from each component turns intuition into engineering. Start by receiving known signals with the bare dongle, then add LNA and filter one at a time, measuring the difference.","scope":"Build the receiver: RTL-SDR/HackRF setup with low-noise amplifier (LNA) and band-pass filter, gain optimization, receive-chain noise figure estimation, and decoding setup for LoRa/RTTY/APRS. Quantify sensitivity improvement from LNA + filter.","deliverables":["Complete SDR receive chain","Sensitivity test report","Decoding software configuration"],"linkages":["Avionics, Software"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-004","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"Antenna Rotator Control & Auto-Tracking Software","skills":"Geodesy math (az/el from lat/lon/alt), hamlib/rotctl, control software, Python","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Given the balloon's GPS position and the station's location, where should the antenna point? The math is satellite-tracking geodesy in miniature: convert two lat/lon/altitude coordinates into a local azimuth/elevation pointing vector, accounting for Earth's curvature \u2014 at 300 km range and 30 km altitude, the balloon sits barely above the horizon. This project writes the software that closes the loop: parse live telemetry, compute pointing angles, drive the BSAT-MEC-2026-003 rotator via the standard rotctl/hamlib protocol, and \u2014 the clever part \u2014 dead-reckon during telemetry dropouts by extrapolating the trajectory, so the antenna keeps pointing at where the balloon should be, which is exactly what recovers the link. Start by implementing and unit-testing the az/el math against an online satellite-pass calculator.","scope":"The software half of BSAT-MEC-2026-003: compute azimuth/elevation to the balloon from live GPS telemetry, drive the rotator (rotctl/hamlib protocol), predictive pointing during telemetry dropouts, plus manual override joystick mode and a pointing-error dashboard.","deliverables":["Auto-tracking software","Dropout prediction mode","Tracking accuracy analysis from flight"],"linkages":["Software, Mechanisms"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-005","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"Ground Station Integration & Mission Control Room","skills":"Systems integration, networking, RF station practices, technical documentation","difficulty":"Medium  |  3 students","summary":"Antennas, rotator, SDR, decoders, database, dashboard \u2014 individually working pieces are not a ground station until someone integrates them, and integration is where projects usually fail. This is the systems-engineering project of the ground segment: define the end-to-end architecture (RF \u2192 digital \u2192 network \u2192 displays), do the unglamorous critical work (cable and connector standards, grounding and lightning protection, UPS backup power, labeling), write the operator manual and checklists, and run full-dress rehearsals tracking a transmitter driven around in a car. On launch day this team operates the station. The mindset is reliability: every single-point failure identified and mitigated. Start by drawing the complete signal-flow diagram with every cable, connector and power source named.","scope":"Systems-integration project: assemble the full ground station (antennas \u2192 rotator \u2192 SDR \u2192 decoders \u2192 network \u2192 dashboard), define the station architecture, cabling/grounding/lightning safety, UPS backup power, operator procedures and station checklists.","deliverables":["Fully integrated ground station","Architecture document","Operator manual & checklists"],"linkages":["All subsystem teams"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-006","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"Mobile Chase Ground Station","skills":"Portable RF systems, power management, vehicle integration, field testing","difficulty":"Beginner  |  2 students","summary":"The chase team drives toward the predicted landing zone while the balloon is still falling \u2014 and they need live telemetry in the car, far from the main station. This project packs a complete receive capability into a grab-and-go kit: magnetic-mount whip antenna on the roof, LoRa receiver or SDR with a laptop or phone, battery power for hours, offline maps, all working while moving. The constraints differ from the fixed station: multipath and obstruction at ground level slash range (quantify it with drive testing), power is finite, and setup time matters \u2014 under five minutes from trunk to tracking. Field robustness (vibration, heat, coffee spills) is part of the spec. Start by benchmarking how far you can receive your transmitter from a moving car with the simplest possible setup, then improve the weakest link.","scope":"Build a car-portable station for the recovery team: magnetic-mount antenna, LoRa receiver + laptop/phone decoding, battery power, offline mapping. Must set up in under 5 minutes and receive the payload from 20+ km while driving.","deliverables":["Complete chase station kit","Drive-test range report","Quick-setup procedure"],"linkages":["Avionics, Software"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-007","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"RF Link Budget & Propagation Analysis","skills":"RF propagation theory, link budget math, RSSI data analysis, site surveying","difficulty":"Medium  |  2 students","summary":"Will the link actually work at 300 km? Link budget analysis answers that question before launch day, in decibels: transmit power, antenna gains, free-space path loss (Friis equation), fade margins for polarization mismatch and payload swing, receiver sensitivity including the LNA's noise figure. This project is the analytical backbone of the entire radio system \u2014 it validates every other RF team's choices, selects the ground station site (horizon obstructions matter when the balloon is 1\u00b0 above the horizon at maximum range), and computes the radio horizon vs altitude. After the flight comes the payoff: comparing predicted against measured RSSI across the entire trajectory, one of the most satisfying validation exercises in the program. Start by building a link budget spreadsheet and sanity-checking it against published LoRa HAB records.","scope":"The analytical backbone of the radio system: full link budget (TX power, antenna gains, path loss at 30 km slant range, fade margin), Fresnel zone/horizon analysis, site survey of the ground station location, and validation against measured RSSI from the flight.","deliverables":["Link budget document","Station site survey report","Predicted vs measured rssi study"],"linkages":["Avionics, Science Payload"]},{"code":"BSAT-GND-2026-008","prefix":"GND","subsystem":"GROUND STATION & COMMUNICATION SEGMENT","title":"Multi-Station Network & Community Receivers","skills":"IoT/networked systems, Raspberry Pi, server backend, distributed systems basics","difficulty":"Advanced  |  3 students","summary":"One receiver station has gaps \u2014 terrain blocks low elevations, local noise raises the floor, and a single point of failure risks losing flight data. The amateur HAB community solved this with distributed listener networks, where volunteer stations worldwide forward received packets to a central server. This project builds a miniature version: two or three low-cost autonomous receiver nodes (Raspberry Pi + SDR + omni antenna) deployed at distributed sites \u2014 other campuses, students' homes \u2014 forwarding packets over the internet to an aggregation server that merges and deduplicates streams. As a stretch goal, differences in packet timing and signal strength across stations enable rough multilateration \u2014 estimating the balloon's position without its GPS. Start with one autonomous node that survives a week unattended, then replicate.","scope":"Scale beyond one station: deploy 2\u20133 low-cost LoRa receiver nodes (Raspberry Pi + RTL-SDR) at distributed sites, aggregate packets over the internet (amateur networks/custom server), improving coverage and enabling rough multilateration experiments.","deliverables":["3-node receiver network","Aggregation server","Coverage improvement analysis"],"linkages":["Software, Avionics, Data Handling"]}]};
